<Layout title="Probate by State: What to Expect Where You Live" description="A state-by-state reference for probate basics — small estate thresholds, simplified probate availability, and typical timelines. Not legal advice.">

<div class="page-hero">
  <h1>Probate Basics by State</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">A reference for what to expect in your state. Not legal advice — an orientation so you know whether to call an attorney or handle it yourself.</p>
</div>

<div class="card card-caution">
  <p><strong>This information is for general orientation only. It is not legal advice.</strong> Probate laws change. Thresholds are updated. Procedures vary by county. Verify current requirements with your state's probate court or an estate attorney before taking action.</p>
  <p style="margin-top:.5rem;font-size:0.85rem;">Last verified: April 2026. Thresholds that adjust for inflation (California, Michigan, others) may have changed. When in doubt, confirm with your state court.</p>
</div>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What probate is — briefly</h2>
  <p>Probate is the legal process of settling a deceased person's estate: validating their will, paying debts, and distributing assets to beneficiaries. <strong>Not every estate requires probate.</strong> Assets that pass by joint ownership, beneficiary designation, or trust typically bypass probate entirely. If the estate is small enough, a simplified affidavit process may be available instead of full probate.</p>
  <p>The table below shows the small estate threshold for each state — the amount below which you may be able to use a simplified process instead of going through the courts.</p>
</section>

<div style="overflow-x: auto; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<table style="width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:0.875rem; font-family: var(--sans);">
  <thead>
    <tr style="border-bottom:2px solid var(--border); text-align:left;">
      <th style="padding:.6rem .75rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600;">State</th>
      <th style="padding:.6rem .75rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600;">Small Estate Threshold</th>
      <th style="padding:.6rem .75rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600;">Simplified Available</th>
      <th style="padding:.6rem .75rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600;">Typical Timeline</th>
      <th style="padding:.6rem .75rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600;">Notes</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    {states.map((row, i) => (
      <tr style={`border-bottom:1px solid var(--border); background: ${i % 2 === 0 ? 'var(--paper)' : 'var(--cream)'}`}>
        <td style="padding:.55rem .75rem; font-weight:500; white-space:nowrap;">{row.state}</td>
        <td style="padding:.55rem .75rem; white-space:nowrap;">{row.threshold}</td>
        <td style="padding:.55rem .75rem; text-align:center;">{row.simplified}</td>
        <td style="padding:.55rem .75rem; white-space:nowrap;">{row.timeline}</td>
        <td style="padding:.55rem .75rem; color:var(--text-muted); font-size:0.8rem;">{row.notes}</td>
      </tr>
    ))}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Community property states</h2>
  <p>The following states are community property states, where property acquired during marriage is generally owned equally by both spouses: Arizona, California, Idaho, Louisiana, Nevada, New Mexico, Texas, Washington, and Wisconsin. If the deceased was married and lived in one of these states, the community property rules significantly affect which assets go through probate and which pass automatically to the surviving spouse.</p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What "simplified probate" means in practice</h2>
  <p>Most states offer a simplified process for small estates — typically an affidavit (a sworn statement) that the successor presents to the institution holding the assets. Instead of going to court, you complete a form, attach a certified death certificate, and present it to the bank, financial institution, or DMV.</p>
  <p>Key limitations of simplified probate:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Must wait a certain period after death (typically 30–45 days, sometimes 60)</li>
    <li>The estate value must fall below the state's threshold (often excluding certain assets)</li>
    <li>Some states only allow it for personal property, not real estate</li>
    <li>If there are disputes among heirs, simplified probate may not be available</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<div class="can-wait">
  <p>If the word "probate" is making you anxious, that's normal. For most estates — especially smaller ones — the process is more paperwork than courtroom. Many states allow simplified probate that takes a few forms and a few weeks. An estate attorney can tell you in one consultation whether your situation is simple or complex. That consultation is often worth the fee just for the peace of mind.</p>
</div>

<div class="emotional-note">
  <p>Government systems are slow. Probate courts are slow. That is not your fault and it is not a reflection of how well you're managing. You are doing this while grieving. The fact that you looked up the process is already more than most people manage in the first weeks.</p>
</div>

</Layout>
